To print "Hello World" 5 times in Java, you can use a loop. The simplest loop for this job is the `for` loop. Here's how you can do it:

```java
public class HelloWorld {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Loop 5 times
        for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
            // Print "Hello World" each time
            System.out.println("Hello World");
        }
    }
}
```

Explanation:

- `public class HelloWorld` defines a public class named `HelloWorld`. This is the container for our program code.
- `public static void main(String[] args)` is the entry point for the Java program. This method is called when the program starts.
- `for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) { ... }` defines a for loop that will iterate 5 times. The `i++` part means that `i` is incremented by 1 in each iteration, starting from 0 and ending before it reaches 5.
- `System.out.println("Hello World");` is used to print "Hello World" to the console. This line executes 5 times because it’s inside the loop.

You can copy this program into a file named `HelloWorld.java`, compile it with `javac HelloWorld.java`, and run it with the `java HelloWorld` command, assuming you have the Java Development Kit (JDK) installed on your machine.

